abstract={Brazil has made tremendous progress in reducing poverty and tackling income inequality too under the tutelage of its current president Dilma Rousseff. In fact, income redistribution has become one of the pillars of Brazil's growth model. A commonly used measure of inequality is the Gini index. According to this measure, inequality has declined at an average rate of 1.2% per year, and experts suggest that even without any growth in GDP per capita, the Millennium Development Goal of reducing poverty by half between 1990 and 2015 would have been met on time. Old-age pensions have also reduced poverty and inequality. Rising pension benefits have been effective in reducing inequality because pension beneficiaries tend to have below average incomes. In fact, Brazil redistributes a larger share of national income to the elderly than any other Latin American country.},
