abstract={In the first section of this paper I look at how the allocation of ODA has improved in the 1990s. This may seem something of a digression, but it turns out to provide a useful benchmark for looking at the allocation of other official flows. Section 2 then takes up the issue of the allocation of non-aid ODF, and Section 3 focuses on technical assistance. The main conclusions of this note are as follows. The allocation of ODA has improved in the 1990s; by 1997-98, there was a clear relationship between the volume of aid and the quality of policies, after controlling for the level of income; by one estimate, the productivity of aid-in delivering poverty reduction-has doubled since 1990. We do not have the same research basis for advising on the allocation of non-aid official finance; in general, the non-aid flows are allocated away from countries with good investment ratings (which makes sense); beyond that, however, there is no tendency to favor good policy or countries in which policy has been improving; it is difficult to find much rationale for the allocation of non-aid official finance, except that it is clearly used to address financial crises (East Asia in the late 1990s, Latin America in the early 1990s); if non-aid resources had the same relationship to good policy that ODA now does, flows would be reduced to Russia (which has poor policy) and to China (which has good market access) and increased to the Philippines and Mexico. Technical assistance-like financial ODA-is allocated in favor of good policy; however, TA's relationship with good policy is not as strong as the relationship for financial aid; thus, TA's share in ODA is large for poor policy countries and smaller for good policy ones, which seems a sensible allocation rule.},
