abstract={The debt crisis hit Latin America in 1982 when Mexico admitted that it could not service its foreign debts. Capital flows into the region dried up and economic development ceased. Per capita incomes fell as governments attempted to pay back their debts to the world's bankers. The poor bore the brunt of the efforts to pay interest on those loans. Governments slashed subsidies on food, light and transportation. Unemployment increased as private factories closed and governments laid off workers. Inflation rose throughout the region, cutting real incomes. The informal employment sector expanded. Nevertheless, unemployment continued to rise. The quality of housing deteriorated as people could not afford to improve their self-help housing. The place of urban growth slowed as cityward migration slackened. The population of the dominant cities of Latin America increased slowly during the 1980s. The prospects for the 1990s are better but variable. Some economies are now beginning to grow, but the prospect for the poor are anything but good. -from Author},
