abstract={A survival type of patron-client relationships which contribute to the survival of impoverished Brazilian urbanites is the subject of this paper. The study site is a large, old squatter settlement in Salvador, Bahia. Previous scholarship on urban patron-client relationships in Latin America is limited and there is lack of agreement on the characteristics of the tie. My analysis suggests that a specific kind of patron-client tie exists in this settlement, the survival type, and that is takes three forms: the political, the economic, and the domestic. It is shaped by survival problems, the kind of access to would-be clients and patrons, occupation, community position, and gender. The forms vary in affect, dependence, and content of the exchange. The relationship is an important means of supplementing household income, especially towards the end of each month when survival problems are severe. The ties are found dispersed across household networks. One implication of this dispersion is that these relationships, rather than enhancing vertical solidarity, contribute to the maintenance of the social class structure in Salvador and potentially Brazil. © 1984 by the Ohio Valley Sociological Society.},
